\subsection{Selected Model and Motivation}
This thesis focuses on XGBoost (Extreme Gradient Boosting) as the duo 
forecasting model. XGBoost is a gradient boosting algorithm that builds an ensemble 
of decision trees sequentially, where each tree corrects the residual errors of the 
previous one \citep{chen2016xgboost}.
\\\\
XGBoost is particularly works well with this project for three reasons. First, it 
handles tabular data with mixed feature types effectively \citep{chen2016xgboost}. This is relevant because it combines sales history, weather and calendar features in the dataset. Second, it is robust to outliers and missing values. This is important given the data quality mentioned in the Data Understanding 
chapter. Third, and most importantly for this project, XGBoost produces feature 
importance scores that quantify the contribution of each input variable to the 
model's predictions \citep{carmona2022black}. Combined with SHAP values, XGBoost will be a good way for explainable demand forecasting.

